import ShellLiveVsResultFlow from "../../../components/diagrams/ShellLiveVsResultFlow.astro";
---

<ChapterShell chapterId="02" locale="en">
  <div slot="thesis">
    <p>
      When a Tool call both changes the world and emits a huge payload, how do you keep evidence of
      what happened without crushing the next inference in the same Turn? The answer is not blunt
      truncation — separate fact, raw bytes, evidence, and context, then hold:
      <strong>Prune the context, never prune the evidence.</strong>
    </p>
  </div>

  <Section
    id="scene"
    label="§02 · Scene"
    title="Start from a gigantic test log"
    lede="The same Tool Result triggers four needs at once — one JSON blob cannot carry all of them."
  >
    <p>
      Suppose the user asks Maka to fix a failing test. The model calls Bash; the test process dumps
      80,000 lines. That result must simultaneously:
    </p>
    <ol class="plain-list numbered">
      <li>Show the model the critical errors so it can choose the next step;</li>
      <li>Leave replayable Bash call/result facts in the Runtime;</li>
      <li>Keep full raw logs recoverable later — a one-line summary is not enough;</li>
      <li>Keep the next model call in the same Turn from carrying all 80,000 lines again.</li>
    </ol>
    <p>
      Stuffing forever into the prompt wrecks the budget; deleting destroys auditability; letting the
      model claim “I verified” mixes observation with judgment. The real question is not “how many
      characters to truncate,” but: what must be durable, what can be rebuilt, and what should live
      only briefly in the model’s working set?
    </p>
  </Section>

  <Section
    id="keystone"
    label="§02 · Keystone"
    title="Turn-level evidence pipeline"
    lede="Scene-local metaphor; the fixed system is NewsLiquid tokens, hand keystones, and motion discipline."
  >
    <DiagramFigure
      prototype
      caption="Fig. 1 · A Tool Result splits into four representations; only path 05 (Provider messages) is the active-prune rewrite surface — 01–04 are not “deletable evidence.”"
      alt="Pipeline from Tool execution to Runtime Event, Artifact, Turn Evidence, then Provider messages; 01–04 persist as evidence; 05 may be pruned; invariant: Prune the context, never prune the evidence."
    >
      <EvidencePipelineKeystone />
    </DiagramFigure>

    <p class="figure-note">
      Invariant: <strong>Prune the context, never prune the evidence.</strong>
      Active prune rewrites only the terminal provider-visible projection — it is not a retention
      policy.
    </p>
  </Section>

  <Section
    id="four"
    label="§02 · Four representations"
    title="One Tool Result, four representations"
    lede="Evidence compression may change how the model later sees a fact — not whether the fact occurred."
  >
    <DiagramFigure
      caption="Fig. 2 · Same result as Durable Fact / Raw Artifact / Turn Evidence / Ephemeral Working Context — distinct authority and lifecycle."
      alt="Four columns: Runtime Fact, Artifact, Turn Evidence, Working context."
    >
      <FourRepsFlow />
    </DiagramFigure>

    <div class="table-wrap" role="region" aria-label="Four representations: question, authority, lifecycle" tabindex="0">
      <table class="proto-table">
        <thead>
          <tr>
            <th scope="col">Representation</th>
            <th scope="col">Question answered</th>
            <th scope="col">Authority</th>
            <th scope="col">Lifecycle</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr>
            <td>Canonical Runtime Fact</td>
            <td>What was called and returned</td>
            <td>Interaction semantics</td>
            <td>Durable ledger</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Raw Artifact</td>
            <td>Where is the full payload; can it be verified</td>
            <td>Raw bytes</td>
            <td>Independent store + hash</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Turn Evidence</td>
            <td>Which public observations remain worth consuming</td>
            <td>Source-bearing derived</td>
            <td>Bounded / rebuildable</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Model Working Context</td>
            <td>Minimum the next step must see</td>
            <td>Ephemeral projection</td>
            <td>Recomputed per request</td>
          </tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>

    <pre class="code-block" aria-label="Four-layer pipeline">Tool execution
  → RuntimeEvent(function_call / function_response)
  → Artifact(raw payload)
  → TurnEvidence(source-bearing bounded projection)
  → Provider Messages(current working set)</pre>

    <p>
      These are not simple copies: RuntimeEvent holds semantics; Artifact holds large payloads;
      Evidence holds source, summary, and integrity; Provider Messages serve the current decision and
      may be trimmed, compacted, or reordered.
    </p>
  </Section>

  <Section
    id="tool-runtime"
    label="§02 · ToolRuntime"
    title="ToolRuntime is the side-effect boundary"
    lede="Not a thin wrapper around tool.impl — guard and permission failures still leave a pairable tool result."
  >
    <DiagramFigure
      caption="Fig. 3 · ToolRuntime in six beats: persist call → guards → permission → execute → normalize tool_result → async artifact."
      alt="Six-step swimlane: Persist call, Guards, Permission, Execute, tool_result, async Artifact; footnotes on synthetic error results and pairing."
    >
      <ToolRuntimeSwimlane />
    </DiagramFigure>
    <ol class="plain-list numbered">
      <li>Persist <code>tool_call</code> and emit <code>tool_start</code>;</li>
      <li>Guards: loop gate, step availability, in-Turn concurrency caps;</li>
      <li>Permission evaluate: allow / block / prompt (wait for the user when needed);</li>
      <li>Run real <code>impl</code>: propagate abort; allow output deltas;</li>
      <li>Normalize and persist <code>tool_result</code> (paired to the call by <code>toolCallId</code>);</li>
      <li>Best-effort async artifact derive — a recorder failure must not mutate the result.</li>
    </ol>
    <p>
      Unloaded tools, denied permission, repeated identical failures, sub-agent concurrency
      overflow — these paths <strong>do not vanish silently</strong>. ToolRuntime writes a synthetic
      error tool result so both the model and the RuntimeEvent ledger know the call was refused and
      why. A function call without a result breaks history pairing and leaves Evidence unable to tell
      “never executed” from “explicitly refused at the boundary.”
    </p>
  </Section>

  <Section
    id="layers"
    label="§02 · Layers"
    title="output / result / artifact are not the same thing"
    lede="Prune never “deletes the tool output” — separate streaming progress, structured results, and independent payloads."
  >
    <ul class="plain-list">
      <li>
        <strong>output delta</strong> — in-flight streaming progress; may feed the UI; not the
        authoritative next-step fact.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>tool result</strong> — structured outcome the model acts on next; enters the ledger
        and pairing.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>artifact</strong> — file, diff, or large payload worth independent storage and
        display; own lifecycle and checksum.
      </li>
    </ul>
    <p>
      Current derivation is conservative: Write may derive a file, Edit a diff, Bash only explicit
      stdout redirects. Recorder failures emit warnings only; slow recorders do not block returning
      the result to the model. Ordinary ArtifactRecords today may not fully carry
      <code>toolCallId</code> / RuntimeEvent refs — Target TurnEvidence must add that source linkage
      rather than pretend it already exists.
    </p>
  </Section>

  <Section
    id="shell-side-effects"
    label="§02 · Shell / PTY"
    title="Side-effect stack: three spawn paths and output channels"
    lede="Bash is not one exec. Managed, local foreground, and workspace-executor differ in sandbox insertion and output authority; PTY mutually excludes mandatory sandboxed argv."
  >
    <DiagramFigure
      caption="Fig. 4a · Three paths: Managed Bash (optional transform) → ShellRun; local foreground (no ShellRun store); workspace executor (isolation: none). Bottom bar pins PTY mutual exclusion."
      alt="Flow: Managed Bash via transformCommand to foreground pipes or background pipes/pty; other paths are local foreground and workspace executor; footer PTY vs sandbox argv mutual exclusion."
    >
      <ShellSpawnTreeFlow />
    </DiagramFigure>

    <h3 class="subhead">Spawn decision tree</h3>
    <pre class="code-block" aria-label="Three spawn paths">buildManagedBashTool
  → transformCommand? (sandboxCommand)
  → ShellRunProcessManager
       ├─ Foreground: pipes only → PipeProcessDriver → terminalContent
       └─ Background: pipes | pty → persistObservation + shell_run ref

buildLocalForegroundBashTool → runShellWithBoundedTail (no ShellRun store)
LocalWorkspaceExecutor → Read/Write/Edit/Glob (+ optional bash) · isolation: 'none'</pre>

    <p>
      The Desktop mainline uses <code>buildManagedBashTool</code>:
      <code>builtin-tools</code> wires <code>transformCommand</code> to
      <code>sandboxCommand</code> → <code>SandboxManager.transform</code>, yielding
      <code>&#123; argv, cwd, env, fdInputs, sandboxType &#125;</code>. Approval
      (PermissionEngine) is orthogonal to sandbox transform — see
      <a href={localePath("en", "chapters/01-log-is-the-runtime") + "#sandbox"}>§01 · #sandbox</a>;
      this section pins the <strong>insertion point and spawn honesty</strong>.
    </p>

    <h3 class="subhead">Sandbox insertion (Current)</h3>
    <ul class="plain-list">
      <li>Non-PTY managed bash: <code>SandboxManager.transform</code> (Seatbelt / bwrap / none).</li>
      <li>PTY + escalation grant → <code>sandboxType: 'none'</code> (explicit escalate, not silent host).</li>
      <li>PTY + profile requires sandbox → <strong>throw</strong> (unavailable, not degrade-to-host).</li>
      <li>Other PTY → no transform (raw shell command).</li>
      <li>
        Manager throws <strong>before spawn</strong> when
        <code>mode === 'pty' &amp;&amp; (argv || fdInputs)</code> — sandboxed argv/fd and PTY are
        mutually exclusive.
      </li>
      <li>
        <code>LocalWorkspaceExecutor</code> fixes <code>isolation: 'none'</code>: sync file tools are
        not an OS sandbox; do not conflate with §01 Seatbelt.
      </li>
    </ul>

    <DiagramFigure
      caption="Fig. 4b · Live emitOutput and retained tool result / shell_run are independent channels: live may suppress while the command continues; the final result still gets the retained tail."
      alt="Process output forks: live emitOutput hits LIVE_EMIT cap then suppress; retained hits RETAINED cap into foreground terminal or background shell_run checkpoint."
    >
      <ShellLiveVsResultFlow />
    </DiagramFigure>

    <div class="table-wrap" role="region" aria-label="Output channels" tabindex="0">
      <table class="proto-table">
        <thead>
          <tr>
            <th scope="col">Channel</th>
            <th scope="col">Bound</th>
            <th scope="col">Consumer</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr>
            <td>Live <code>emitOutput</code></td>
            <td><code>BASH_MAX_LIVE_EMIT_CHARS</code> then suppress marker</td>
            <td>UI stream</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Retained tail</td>
            <td><code>BASH_MAX_RETAINED_CHARS</code></td>
            <td>Final tool result</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Foreground result</td>
            <td><code>shapeTerminalResult</code> + model truncate</td>
            <td>function_response</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Background result</td>
            <td><code>shell_run</code> ref + PTY model text budget</td>
            <td>Model + Read ref</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Persisted checkpoint</td>
            <td>shell-run-store revision</td>
            <td>Recovery / UI</td>
          </tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>

    <p>
      <strong>Key separation:</strong> after the live cap, a suppress marker may fire while the
      process keeps running; the tool result still receives the retained tail. Same shape as “output
      delta ≠ tool result” above — Bash makes it two measurable caps.
    </p>

    <div class="table-wrap" role="region" aria-label="Shell failure matrix" tabindex="0">
      <table class="proto-table proto-table--fail">
        <thead>
          <tr>
            <th scope="col">Failure</th>
            <th scope="col">Surface</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr>
            <td>Timeout</td>
            <td>exit 124 / <code>timed_out</code></td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Abort</td>
            <td>exit 130 / <code>cancelled</code></td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Live flood</td>
            <td>suppress marker; result still retains the tail</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Sandbox denial (output heuristic)</td>
            <td><code>sandboxDenial.likely</code> on terminal</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>PTY + argv/fdInputs</td>
            <td>throw before spawn</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Persist failure</td>
            <td>live may lag durable state — never pretend a checkpoint landed</td>
          </tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>

    <aside class="history-aside">
      <p class="history-aside__tag">Evolution aside · mechanism</p>
      <p>
        Bounded recoverable Bash output:
        <a href={localePath("en", "history/pr/92")}>maka:pr:92</a>. Background shell_run refs:
        <a href={localePath("en", "history/pr/547")}>maka:pr:547</a>. PTY + stdin control:
        <a href={localePath("en", "history/pr/778")}>maka:pr:778</a>. Tests:
        <code>shell-exec.test.ts</code> · <code>shell-tools.test.ts</code> ·
        <code>shell-run-manager.test.ts</code> · <code>pty-screen-collector.test.ts</code> ·
        <code>workspace-executor.test.ts</code>. Outline:
        <code>docs/research/shell-pty-executor-deep-outline.md</code> (#56 → Task #68).
      </p>
    </aside>
  </Section>

  <Section
    id="turn"
    label="§02 · Boundary"
    title="Why Turn is the natural Evidence boundary"
    lede="Steps are too fine; Sessions are too wide; Turn is the operable midpoint."
  >
    <DiagramFigure
      caption="Fig. 4 · Source chain: RuntimeEvent → Artifact → Turn Evidence → later consumers; raw remains fetchable by ref."
      alt="Four steps: RuntimeEvent, Artifact ref, Turn Evidence, Later consumer."
    >
      <SourceChainFlow />
    </DiagramFigure>
    <p>
      Model/tool events in this round share a <code>turnId</code>; tool call/result, permission, and
      artifacts can belong to the same round; a Turn terminal fact marks completed / failed /
      aborted. The next Turn can treat prior Evidence as bounded engineering memory without expanding
      every raw dump.
    </p>
    <p>Turn Evidence should be able to answer:</p>
    <pre class="code-block" aria-label="Questions Evidence must answer">What was this Turn trying to accomplish?
Which tools did it actually call?
What public results were observed?
Which artifacts were produced or mutated?
Which outputs were truncated, archived, or omitted?
Which canonical facts and raw payloads do the summaries point back to?</pre>
    <p>
      It must <strong>not</strong> answer “an official verifier certainly passed,” nor replace Runtime
      terminal status. Evidence describes sourced observations; conclusions and authoritative outcomes
      live elsewhere (see §05).
    </p>
  </Section>

  <Section
    id="active"
    label="§02 · Active prune"
    title="Active prune: same-Turn request shaping"
    lede="Archive before omission. Fail open. A provider request-shaping policy — not a retention policy."
  >
    <DiagramFigure
      caption="Fig. 5 · Active prune protocol: Hash → Archive OK? → placeholder / keep original → next provider step; ledger dashed bypass never moves."
      alt="Decision diamond: Archive OK yields source-bearing placeholder, else keep original fail open; RuntimeEvent/Session ledger dashed as unrewritten."
    >
      <ActivePruneFlow />
    </DiagramFigure>

    <p>
      Stale pruning handles prior-history replay; Active Tool Result Prune answers the sharper
      question: Step 1 just produced a huge tool result — must Step 2 resend it verbatim? It runs in
      the AI SDK <code>prepareStep</code> hook — between the end of one provider step and assembly of
      the next — and only touches eligible large results from completed steps in the current Turn.
    </p>

    <p>Protocol (numbered on the page):</p>
    <ol class="plain-list numbered">
      <li>
        Eligible: completed steps in the current Turn; over the estimated-token threshold (Desktop
        default ~2048 — a <strong>policy knob, not a protocol constant</strong>);
      </li>
      <li>Stable-serialize → compute <code>bodySha256</code> / bytes / estimate;</li>
      <li>Host archive writer must return a non-empty <code>artifactId</code>;</li>
      <li>Only then build the placeholder;</li>
      <li>Replace only in this <code>prepareStep</code> messages view;</li>
      <li>Ledger / Session persisted results stay <strong>untouched</strong>.</li>
    </ol>

    <p>Placeholder fields (<code>reason</code> enum stays English code in both locales):</p>
    <pre class="code-block" aria-label="Active prune placeholder fields">artifactId, turnId, toolCallId, toolName,
bodySha256, originalEstimatedTokens, originalBytes,
rewriteVersion,
reason = active_current_turn_tool_result_pruned_before_next_step</pre>

    <p>
      Active prune does <strong>not</strong>: delete the ledger; rewrite Session-persisted results;
      summarize business meaning; claim placeholder == full evidence; omit on archive failure to save
      tokens; handle every old historical result.
    </p>

    <aside class="history-aside">
      <p class="history-aside__tag">Evolution aside · mechanism</p>
      <p>
        Mechanism intro:
        <a href={`${localePath("en", "history/pr/316")}`}>maka:pr:316</a>
        (Add active tool result pruning). Archive-before-placeholder discipline:
        <a href={`${localePath("en", "history/pr/319")}`}>maka:pr:319</a>
        (require archived active tool pruning). Default-on:
        <a href={`${localePath("en", "history/pr/498")}`}>maka:pr:498</a>. Docs land (secondary):
        <a href={`${localePath("en", "history/pr/769")}`}>maka:pr:769</a>.
      </p>
    </aside>
  </Section>

  <Section
    id="stale"
    label="§02 · Three lifecycles"
    title="Three lifecycles: Active · Stale · History compact"
    lede="They share prune / archive / placeholder vocabulary but differ in when they fire, what they mutate, and how they fail — collapsing them into one “compaction” story is a classic teaching failure."
  >
    <DiagramFigure
      caption="Fig. 6 · Three lifecycles side by side: Active (same-Turn messages) · Stale (compact input projection) · History compact (checkpoint over a covered prefix)."
      alt="Three columns: Active prune, Stale prune, History compact — mutate surface, placeholder kind, fail-open."
    >
      <ThreePruneLifecyclesFlow />
    </DiagramFigure>

    <DiagramFigure
      caption="Fig. 6b · Active vs Stale pressure contrast (History compact in the table + §03) — do not swap “current Turn” for “replay history.”"
      alt="Two columns: Active same Turn prepareStep; Stale prior history."
    >
      <ActiveVsStaleFlow />
    </DiagramFigure>

    <div class="table-wrap" role="region" aria-label="Three-lifecycle protocol contrast" tabindex="0">
      <table class="proto-table">
        <thead>
          <tr>
            <th scope="col"></th>
            <th scope="col">Active prune</th>
            <th scope="col">Stale prune</th>
            <th scope="col">History compact</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr>
            <th scope="row">Code</th>
            <td><code>active-tool-result-prune.ts</code></td>
            <td><code>tool-result-archive.ts</code> · <code>pruneStaleToolResultsBeforeCompact</code></td>
            <td><code>history-compact*.ts</code> (body in §03)</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <th scope="row">When</th>
            <td>Same Turn · <code>prepareStep</code></td>
            <td>Immediately before a compact pass</td>
            <td>Turn boundary / mid-turn shaping</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <th scope="row">Mutates</th>
            <td>In-memory <code>ModelMessage[]</code> for this request only</td>
            <td>RuntimeEvent <strong>projection</strong> fed to the compactor</td>
            <td>Model-visible projection: covered prefix → checkpoint block</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <th scope="row">Placeholder kind</th>
            <td><code>maka.active_archived_tool_result</code></td>
            <td><code>maka.archived_tool_result</code></td>
            <td><code>maka.history_compact_checkpoint</code></td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <th scope="row">reason code</th>
            <td><code>active_current_turn_tool_result_pruned_before_next_step</code></td>
            <td><code>stale_tool_result_pruned_before_compact</code></td>
            <td>(checkpoint coverage / digest — not a tool-result reason)</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <th scope="row">Guard band</th>
            <td><code>minStepNumber</code> (default 1; step 0 untouched)</td>
            <td><code>minRecentTurnsFull</code> newest N turns stay full</td>
            <td>Safe completed span · reserve tail · never straddle a tool pair</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <th scope="row">Failure</th>
            <td><code>archiveFailures</code> → <strong>keep original</strong></td>
            <td>Missing/mismatched <code>archiveRef</code> → keep + <code>archiveWriteFailures</code></td>
            <td>Fail-open: no false coverage (see §03)</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <th scope="row">Durable ledger</th>
            <td>Never rewritten</td>
            <td>Does not claim to rewrite the authority ledger; swaps the projection’s result view</td>
            <td>Canonical RuntimeEvent ledger stays authoritative; checkpoint is verifiable</td>
          </tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>

    <h3 class="subhead">Stale prune protocol (source-level)</h3>
    <p>
      <code>pruneStaleToolResultsBeforeCompact</code> only touches non-<code>partial</code>
      <code>function_response</code> events outside the protected recent turns and above the size
      threshold. Replacement requires a matching <code>archiveRef</code>:
      <code>archiveRefMatches</code> demands identical <code>bodySha256</code> /
      <code>originalBytes</code> / <code>originalEstimatedTokens</code> / tool identity — otherwise the
      event is <strong>returned unchanged</strong> and counted as a failure, never silently truncated.
      Hydration via <code>retrieveArchivedToolResultsForReplay</code> re-hashes
      <code>sha256(serializedResult)</code> on every read; mismatch → <code>corrupt</code>, never
      pretend damaged bytes are raw.
    </p>

    <h3 class="subhead">Lineage: prune is a representation change, not a forked history</h3>
    <p>
      Active path <code>activeToolResultLineageIdentity()</code> hashes the <strong>raw serialized
      body</strong> and shares that identity between raw payload and placeholder — later stale/compact
      lineage tracking treats prune as a representation change, not a divergent source history. Within
      one prune pass, <code>{'${toolCallId}:${bodySha256}'}</code> reuses the same placeholder to
      avoid double-archiving.
    </p>

    <h3 class="subhead">History compact only owns a boundary slot in this chapter</h3>
    <p>
      The third lifecycle folds a <strong>completed prefix</strong> behind a checkpoint (V2
      <code>sourceDigest</code>, optional <code>phase: mid_turn</code> + <code>headAnchor</code>); it is
      not “run tool-result archive again.” Protocol body, digest match, and fail-open matrix live in
      <a href={localePath("en", "chapters/03-compaction-is-a-projection")}>§03</a>. This chapter’s job
      is: <strong>Active ≠ Stale ≠ Compact</strong> before the reader enters projection semantics.
    </p>

